        <section type="subsection">
          <title>Core and valence electrons</title>
	  <shortcode>ESABK</shortcode>
          <para>Electrons in the outermost energy level of an atom are called <emphasis effect="bold">valence electrons</emphasis>. The electrons that are in the energy shells closer to the nucleus are called <emphasis effect="bold">core electrons</emphasis>. Core electrons are all the electrons in an atom, excluding the valence electrons. An element that has its valence energy level full is <emphasis effect="italics">more stable</emphasis> and <emphasis effect="italics">less likely to react</emphasis> than other elements with a valence energy level that is not full.</para>
          <definition>
            <term>Valence electrons</term>
            <meaning>
              <para>The electrons in the outermost energy level of an atom.</para>
            </meaning>
